        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1879481944" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16870569014382189843">Ted Kooser is not the kind of poet I normally read. I gravitate toward confessional female poets, starting with my obsession with Sylvia Plath in high school. However, I find myself turning to Kooser&apos;s work again and again. His poems are simplistic and graceful, yet brim over with brevity. <br/><br/>In <i>Delights and Shadows</i>, he writes about ageing and the deaths of his mother and grandmother. Domesticity and ordinary objects weigh heavily in Kooser&apos;s poetry: a button, a glassware set, an elderly man&apos;s tatt</span>
  <span id="freeText16870569014382189843" style="display:none">Ted Kooser is not the kind of poet I normally read. I gravitate toward confessional female poets, starting with my obsession with Sylvia Plath in high school. However, I find myself turning to Kooser's work again and again. His poems are simplistic and graceful, yet brim over with brevity. <br /><br />In <i>Delights and Shadows</i>, he writes about ageing and the deaths of his mother and grandmother. Domesticity and ordinary objects weigh heavily in Kooser's poetry: a button, a glassware set, an elderly man's tattoo. My favorite poem this time around (I think this is my second re-reading, but it might be my third) is "Pearl," about an older cousin whom the narrator visits with the sad news of his mother's death. Pearl is ninety years old, and glad for company, but confides to the narrator that she's been seeing ghostly visitors throughout her house, taking stock of her earthly possessions. The poem is only four pages long, but you learn so much about this elderly woman, and the man still reeling from his mother's death. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16870569014382189843" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


